  <chapter number="2" style="c" sid="LUK 2" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 2:1" />Around that time, an edict from Caesar Augustus was issued to the entire civilized world.<verse eid="LUK 2:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 2:2" />This edict was a census<char style="sup">[a]</char>, and this census was the first one issued during
        the tenure of Quirinius, the ruler of <char style="it">the</char> <char style="it">Roman province of
        </char>Syria. <verse eid="LUK 2:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 2:3" />Everyone was either coming or going to be registered, each to the city he belonged to. <verse eid="LUK 2:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 2:4" />So Joseph went from the city of Nazareth in Galilee to Judea, to the city of David, which is called “Bethlehem,”
        on account of him being of the lineage of and being a descendant of David, <verse eid="LUK 2:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 2:5" />to be registered for the census along with his fiancée Mary, who was expecting. <verse eid="LUK 2:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 2:6" />While they were there, her due-date arrived, <verse eid="LUK 2:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 2:7" />and she gave birth to a son, her firstborn, wrapped him in a blanket, and laid him in a manger, since
        there wasn’t any room for them in the upstairs floor of the house they were at<char style="sup">[A]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 2:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 2:8" />Nearby in the same area, there were shepherds working the night shift outdoors, keeping an eye on their
        sheep. <verse eid="LUK 2:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 2:9" />An angel sent from the Lord appeared to them, and the glory of the Lord shined all around them, and they
        became very frightened. <verse eid="LUK 2:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 2:10" />The angel said to them, “Don’t be afraid, since I’m here, you see, to announce to you something good,
        a message about the tremendous grace which will be <char style="it">given</char> to all the people, <verse eid="LUK 2:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 2:11" />since this day a savior, who is Christ the Lord, was born in your midst in the city of David. <verse eid="LUK 2:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 2:12" />This is the way you’ll spot him: you’ll find a baby all wrapped up lying in a manger.” <verse eid="LUK 2:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 2:13" />And suddenly a multitude of troops<char style="sup">[b]</char> from <char style="it">the angels in </char>heaven
        appeared together with the angel praising God, saying <char style="it">over and over</char>,<verse eid="LUK 2:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 2:14" />Glory to God to the max,
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 2:14">And peace <char style="it">be</char> upon the Earth among men of good intent<verse eid="LUK 2:14"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 2:15" />When the angels departed from them back to heaven, the shepherds began saying to one another, “Let’s
        go from one end of Bethlehem to the other, right this moment, until we get to look into this situation,
        this thing that the Lord informed us of.” <verse eid="LUK 2:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 2:16" />They left in a hurry and discovered it: Mary, Joseph, and the baby lying in the manger. <verse eid="LUK 2:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 2:17" />While looking <char style="it">things over</char>, they made known the details of the message spoken
        to them in regard to this very child. <verse eid="LUK 2:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 2:18" />Many of those who had heard what was said were amazed at what the shepherds were telling them; <verse eid="LUK 2:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 2:19" />Mary latched on to all these words while they were being deposited into her heart and collected there.<verse eid="LUK 2:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 2:20" />The shepherds returned glorifying and praising God for everything they heard about and saw, <char style="it">which
        was in fact</char> just like it had been spoken to them.<verse eid="LUK 2:20" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 2:21" />When the eighth day, the day for him to be circumcised, rolled around, they named him “Jesus,” the name
        given by the angel before he was conceived. <verse eid="LUK 2:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 2:22" />And when the purification time, the span of time in accordance with the Old Testament<char style="sup">[c]</char>
        statute, had expired, they took him over to Jerusalem to be presented to the Lord, <verse eid="LUK 2:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 2:23" />just as it’s written in the Old Testament<char style="sup">[c]</char>, “Every man-child who is a mother’s
        first delivery shall be designated as set aside for the Lord<char style="sup">[d]</char>,” <verse eid="LUK 2:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 2:24" />and to offer up a sacrifice according to the commandment in the Old Testament<char style="sup">[c]</char>,
        “a pair of turtledoves or two young doves.”<verse eid="LUK 2:24" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 2:25" />Now, you see, there was a man in Jerusalem named Simeon, and this fellow was righteous and devout, awaiting
        Israel’s consolation<char style="sup">[e]</char>, and the Holy Spirit was upon him. <verse eid="LUK 2:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 2:26" />He had been informed in a consultation by the Holy Spirit that he won’t encounter death before seeing
        Christ the Lord. <verse eid="LUK 2:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 2:27" />By the Spirit, he went to the temple and to the parents <char style="it">as they were</char> presenting
        the child Jesus, carrying out the Old Testament<char style="sup">[c]</char> ritual concerning him, <verse eid="LUK 2:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 2:28" />and he himself took him into his arms, gave a blessing to God, and said,<verse eid="LUK 2:28" />
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 2:29" />”At this time You’re releasing Your servant
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 2:29">From his service in peace, Master,</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 2:29"><char style="it">Just</char> like You said you would,<verse eid="LUK 2:29"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 2:30" />Because my eyes have seen Your rescue program<char style="sup">[f]</char>,<verse eid="LUK 2:30" />
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 2:31" />That which You’ve prepared in accordance with
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 2:31">The disposition of the people<char style="sup">[g]</char>:<verse eid="LUK 2:31"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 2:32" />A light resulting in a revelation for the nations
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 2:32">And resulting in your people Israel’s high regard<char style="sup">[h]</char>.”<verse eid="LUK 2:32"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="LUK 2:33" />His father and mother were surprised by what was spoken about him. <verse eid="LUK 2:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="LUK 2:34" />Simeon pronounced a blessing on them and said to Mary, “You see, this fellow is destined to be <char
        style="it">the cause of</char> the downfall and rejuvenation<char style="sup">[i]</char> of many in Israel
        and to be a portent<char style="sup">[j]</char> spoken against them. <verse eid="LUK 2:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="LUK 2:35" />And for you—your very life-being<char style="sup">[k]</char> will be gone through with a sword, pierced
        from end to end, so that from out of many hearts, contemplations and reasonings would be revealed.”<verse eid="LUK 2:35" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="LUK 2:36" />There was a prophetess <char style="it">named </char>Anna, daughter of Phanuel, of the tribe of Asher.
        She was up there in years, having married as a young woman, her marriage lasting for seven years, <verse eid="LUK 2:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="LUK 2:37" />and after that being a widow for 84 years, during which time she hadn’t been absent from the temple,
        fasting and praying day and night in service <char style="it">to God</char>. <verse eid="LUK 2:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="LUK 2:38" />At the same time <char style="it">the ritual was going on</char>, she <char style="it">went over</char>
        and stood by <char style="it">their side</char>, all the while professing affirmations in acknowledgement
        to God and speaking about Him to all those in Jerusalem awaiting the rectification of their dire straits<char
        style="sup">[l]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 2:38" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="LUK 2:39" />When all the rituals prescribed by the Old Testament<char style="sup">[c]</char> were concluded, they
        left for Galilee, to their hometown of Nazareth. <verse eid="LUK 2:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="LUK 2:40" />Now the child kept on growing and kept on getting stronger, while being filled with wisdom, and God’s
        favor<char style="sup">[m]</char> was upon him.<verse eid="LUK 2:40" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="LUK 2:41" />Year after year, his parents kept going <char style="it">back</char> to Jerusalem, to the Passover festival,<verse eid="LUK 2:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="LUK 2:42" />and when he was twelve years old, they went to Jerusalem according to festival custom. <verse eid="LUK 2:42" />
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="LUK 2:43" />When the festival, which lasted a few days, was over, as they were departing, the child Jesus remained
        in Jerusalem, but his parents were unaware. <verse eid="LUK 2:43" />
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="LUK 2:44" />Having assumed that he was somewhere in the caravan, they were on the road a few days and began searching
        for him among their relatives and acquaintances, <verse eid="LUK 2:44" />
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="LUK 2:45" />but they weren’t able to find him. They returned to Jerusalem in search of him.<verse eid="LUK 2:45" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="LUK 2:46" />It so happened that after three days they found him in the temple sitting in the middle of the teachers,
        listening to them and asking them questions. <verse eid="LUK 2:46" />
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="LUK 2:47" />All of those who were listening to him were amazed at his understanding—his ability to put things together—and
        at his answers. <verse eid="LUK 2:47" />
      <verse number="48" style="v" sid="LUK 2:48" /><char style="it">Upon </char>seeing this, <char style="it">his parents </char>were taken aback, and his
        mother said to him, “Child, why have you treated us this way? Look—your father and I have been pulling
        our hair out looking for you.” <verse eid="LUK 2:48" />
      <verse number="49" style="v" sid="LUK 2:49" />He said to them, “Just why now were you searching for me? Didn’t you know that I had to be in the midst
        of my Father’s interests<char style="sup">[n]</char>?” <verse eid="LUK 2:49" />
      <verse number="50" style="v" sid="LUK 2:50" />They didn’t put all the pieces together from the remark that was spoken to them. <verse eid="LUK 2:50" />
      <verse number="51" style="v" sid="LUK 2:51" />He left with them and went to Nazareth, and he was staying in submission to their authority. His mother
        in her heart latched on<char style="sup">[o]</char> to all these incidences, one after another; <verse eid="LUK 2:51" />
      <verse number="52" style="v" sid="LUK 2:52" />and Jesus continued forging ahead<char style="sup">[p]</char> in wisdom, stature, and in God’s and in
        peoples’ favor.<verse eid="LUK 2:52" />
    </para>
