  <!--   Chapter  7   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="7" style="c" sid="LUK 7" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 7:1" />Since he finished going through all of his material with those listening—a bunch of ordinary folk<char
        style="sup">[a]</char>—he entered Capernaum. <verse eid="LUK 7:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 7:2" />Now there was this centurion’s servant, whom the centurion<char style="sup">[A]</char> held in high esteem,
        who was sick and about to pass away. <verse eid="LUK 7:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 7:3" />Having heard about Jesus, he sent distinguished, respected Jewish citizens to him, asking him if he would
        come and resuscitate his servant. <verse eid="LUK 7:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 7:4" />Approaching Jesus, they asked him—begged him—to hurry up, saying that this particular individual is worth
        him going out of his way to help, <verse eid="LUK 7:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 7:5" />since he loves and values our people, and that he single-handedly built us a synagogue. <verse eid="LUK 7:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 7:6" />So Jesus proceeded to go with them.
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 7:6">They had already made it to where they were not too far from his house, when the centurion sent some
        of his close friends telling him, “Sir, don’t put yourself out; you see, it’s not appropriate for you
        to set foot in my house for a visit<char style="sup">[b]</char>, <verse eid="LUK 7:6"/>
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 7:7" />seeing that I’m not considered worthy of you associating with me<char style="sup">[c]</char>. Instead,
        just say the word and have my servant receive healing<char style="sup">[B]</char>. <verse eid="LUK 7:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 7:8" />You see, I too am a man who’s under chain-of-command-structured authority<char style="sup">[d]</char>,
        having soldiers under me. I tell this one, ‘Have him go <char style="it">forth</char>,’ and he goes,
        and tell someone else, ‘Come <char style="it">here</char>’ and he comes, and tell<char style="it"> </char>my
        servant, ‘Do this <char style="it">thing</char>,’ and he does it.” <verse eid="LUK 7:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 7:9" />Jesus heard these things and was amazed at him and turned to the crowd following him and said, <char
        style="wj">“I’m telling you what, I haven’t run across such faith </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">anywhere
        else</char></char><char style="wj"> in Israel.”</char> <verse eid="LUK 7:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 7:10" />When they got back home, those who were dispatched found the servant in good health.<verse eid="LUK 7:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 7:11" />The next thing that happened was that he went to a city called Nain, accompanied by his disciples and
        by a large crowd. <verse eid="LUK 7:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 7:12" />As he neared the city gate, he ran across a dead man being carried out, his mother’s only son (and she
        herself was a widow<char style="sup">[C]</char>); a sizable crowd from the city was accompanying her.<verse eid="LUK 7:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 7:13" />Upon seeing her, the Lord felt compassion deep in his heart for her and said, <char style="wj">“Don’t
        cry.” </char><verse eid="LUK 7:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 7:14" />He went over and touched the open coffin<char style="sup">[e]</char>; the pallbearers came to a halt
        and stood still. He said, <char style="wj">“Young man, I’m speaking to you—get up!”</char> <verse eid="LUK 7:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 7:15" />The dead person sat up and began talking, and they handed him over to his mother. <verse eid="LUK 7:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 7:16" />A deep reverence came upon everyone<char style="sup">[f]</char>, and they glorified God saying that a
        great prophet had been brought to prominence<char style="sup">[g]</char> among them, and that God has
        paid a visit to His people. <verse eid="LUK 7:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 7:17" />The news of this affair propagated throughout the entire region of Judea and all the surrounding area.<verse eid="LUK 7:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 7:18" />His disciples told John about all of these things, and John summoned two of his disciples <verse eid="LUK 7:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 7:19" />and sent them to the Lord saying, “Are you the One-Who-Is-To-Come<char style="sup">[h]</char>, or should
        we wait for someone else?” <verse eid="LUK 7:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 7:20" />These men met with him and said, “John the Baptist sent us to you to say, ‘Are you the One-Who-Is-To-Come,
        or should we wait for someone else?’” <verse eid="LUK 7:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 7:21" />During the last couple of hours just then, he had treated many people of diseases, of whatever bad thing
        happened to be beating the tar out of them<char style="sup">[i]</char>, and of evil spirits, and he graciously
        granted many who were blind the gift of sight. <verse eid="LUK 7:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 7:22" />He replied to them, <char style="wj">“Go tell John what you saw and heard: the blind regain their sight,
        the lame walk, lepers are purged of their leprosy, the deaf hear, the dead are resurrected, the destitute
        are told good news— </char><verse eid="LUK 7:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 7:23" /><char style="wj">and blessed is he who isn’t offended with me</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char
        style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="LUK 7:23" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 7:24" />So John’s messengers left, and he proceeded to speak to the crowd about John, <char style="wj">“What
        did you go out to the countryside</char><char style="sup">[D]</char><char style="wj"> to take a look
        at? A twig fluttering in the breeze? </char><verse eid="LUK 7:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 7:25" /><char style="wj">Instead, what did you witness? A man dressed up in delicate apparel</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char
        style="wj">? You see, those wearing splendid attire and living the life of luxury live in palaces. </char><verse eid="LUK 7:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 7:26" /><char style="wj">Rather, what did you go out to see? A prophet?—Yes, I’m telling you, and more than </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">just</char></char><char style="wj"> </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">your
        run-of-the-mill</char></char><char style="wj"> prophet. </char><verse eid="LUK 7:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 7:27" /><char style="wj">This fellow’s been written about in Scripture,</char>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 7:27"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 7:27"><char style="wj">“See here, I will send my messenger</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 7:27"><char style="wj">To where your attention is fixated,</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 7:27"><char style="wj">Who’ll prepare your road ahead of you</char><verse eid="LUK 7:27"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 7:28" /><char style="wj">”I’m telling you, nobody’s ever been born on this planet who’s greater than John</char><char
        style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj">, but the least significant that God’s involved with (in God’s
        kingdom) is greater than he.” </char><verse eid="LUK 7:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 7:29" />Everyone <char style="it">in the crowd </char>who was listening—ordinary folk including tax collectors—had
        affirmed God, making Him the right choice, having been baptized in John’s baptism. <verse eid="LUK 7:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 7:30" />But the Pharisees and the Old Testament<char style="sup">[m]</char> experts disavowed God’s will, plan,
        and purpose for their own selves, not being baptized by him.<verse eid="LUK 7:30" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 7:31" /><char style="wj">“For that matter, in what analogy can I draw a comparison of the men to, the men adhering
        to the present-day Zeitgeist</char><char style="sup">[n]</char><char style="wj">? </char><verse eid="LUK 7:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 7:32" /><char style="wj">They’re comparable to children sitting </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">around</char></char><char
        style="wj"> in the marketplace and calling over to some other </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">children</char></char><char
        style="wj">,</char></para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 7:32"></para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 7:32"><char style="wj">“We played the flute for you, and you wouldn’t dance;</char></para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 7:32"><char style="wj">We sang a dirge, and you wouldn’t weep </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">and
        wail</char></char><char style="sup">[E]</char><verse eid="LUK 7:32"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="LUK 7:33" /><char style="wj">”The fact is, John the Baptist came on the scene not eating bread or drinking wine—</char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">living a life of austerity</char></char><char style="wj">—and you say, ‘He’s
        compelled to do this by a demon.’” </char><verse eid="LUK 7:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="LUK 7:34" /><char style="wj">The Man</char><char style="sup">[o]</char><char style="wj"> came on the scene eating
        and drinking—</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">living the good life</char></char><char style="wj">—and
        you say, ‘Get ahold of this guy—he parties</char><char style="sup">[p]</char><char style="wj"> and hangs
        around tax collectors and </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">other kinds of </char></char><char
        style="wj">sinners.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 7:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="LUK 7:35" /><char style="wj">Wisdom is declared to be correct by the end-result</char><char style="sup">[q]</char><char
        style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="LUK 7:35" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="LUK 7:36" />One of the Pharisees asked if he would dine with him, and he entered the Pharisee’s house and was seated<char
        style="sup">[r]</char>. <verse eid="LUK 7:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="LUK 7:37" />By chance, there was a woman there in that city—a sinner<char style="sup">[F]</char>—and she found out
        that he was dining at the Pharisee’s house, and she took a jar of myrrh <verse eid="LUK 7:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="LUK 7:38" />and stood next to him, across from his feet, sobbing with tears <char style="it">all over</char>. She
        proceeded to rain tears down on his feet, wipe them down with her hair and fervently kiss them, and to
        pour myrrh all over them. <verse eid="LUK 7:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="LUK 7:39" />Seeing this, the Pharisee who invited him over said to himself,
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 7:39">“If this guy were a prophet, he’d be mindful of<char style="sup">[F]</char> who <char style="it">the
        woman is </char>who’s touching him and of what sort of woman she is, since she’s a sinner.”<verse eid="LUK 7:39"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="LUK 7:40" />Jesus’s response to this was, <char style="wj">“Simon, I’d like to tell you something.”</char>
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 7:40">“Speak up, teacher”.<verse eid="LUK 7:40"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="LUK 7:41" /><char style="wj">”There were two debtors. The first one owed $50,000</char><char style="sup">[s]</char><char
        style="wj">, and the second one owed $5,000, both to the same lender. </char><verse eid="LUK 7:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="LUK 7:42" /><char style="wj">Not having the funds with which to repay him, both asked to be let off the hook. So
        now, which of them do you think will be more endeared to him?”</char><verse eid="LUK 7:42" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="LUK 7:43" />Simon answered, “I suppose the one who had the greater amount cancelled will be.”
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 7:43">He said, <char style="wj">“You’ve guessed right.”</char><verse eid="LUK 7:43"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="LUK 7:44" />He turned to the woman and said to Simon, <char style="wj">“See this woman here? I entered your house,
        and you didn’t pour water on my feet </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">in order to wash them</char></char><char
        style="wj">; but she, now, showered my feet with her tears and wiped </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">them
        </char></char><char style="wj">with her hair. </char><verse eid="LUK 7:44" />
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="LUK 7:45" /><char style="wj">You didn’t greet me at the door with a kiss</char><char style="sup">[G]</char><char
        style="wj">; but she, now, hasn’t stopped kissing my feet since the moment she entered </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">the house</char></char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="LUK 7:45" />
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="LUK 7:46" /><char style="wj">You didn’t caress my head with lotion</char><char style="sup">[H]</char><char style="wj">;
        but she, now, covered my feet with special oil—</char><verse eid="LUK 7:46" />
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="LUK 7:47" /><char style="wj">I’m being blunt with you—her sins—and there’s a lot of them—have been forgiven because
        of the volume of love, value, and appreciation that came out of her</char><char style="sup">[t]</char><char
        style="wj">. He who’s been forgiven of little loves, values, and appreciates little.” </char><verse eid="LUK 7:47" />
      <verse number="48" style="v" sid="LUK 7:48" /><char style="wj">He said to her, “Your sins are forgiven.”</char> <verse eid="LUK 7:48" />
      <verse number="49" style="v" sid="LUK 7:49" />The dinner guests started to talk among themselves, “Who is this guy?—He even forgives sins.” <verse eid="LUK 7:49" />
      <verse number="50" style="v" sid="LUK 7:50" />He said to the woman, <char style="wj">“Your faith has rescued you</char><char style="sup">[u]</char><char
        style="wj">; go in peace (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">i.e., go your way free of conflict,
        duress, or affliction</char></char><char style="wj">).”</char><verse eid="LUK 7:50" />
    </para>
