        and city.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[E]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[E]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">We sang a dirge, and you wouldn’t weep</char> <char style="it">and wail</char> …Ref.
        note of Matt. 11:17</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[F]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[F]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">a sinner</char>…<char style="it">be mindful of</char>…Also: (<char style="it">for be
        mindful of</char>) <char style="it">continuously aware of; ever cognizant of</char>. The way that she’s
        singled out as being “a sinner” (v.37) and the verb tense in <char style="it">be mindful of </char>(v.
        39) insinuate that she’s an adulterous or is sexually immoral in some other way. This verse literally
        reads, <char style="it">he would’ve known she was a sinner, </char>leaving the implication that he would’ve
        done something about it.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[G]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[G]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">you didn’t greet me at the door with a kiss</char>…Lit: <char style="it">you didn’t
        give me a kiss</char>. As seen in various places in the NT, it was customary back then to greet someone
        of the same sex with a kiss. The kiss was a cordial greeting, a sign of friendship and comradery. In
        fact, the Gk. word <char style="it">philos</char> (φίλος /Strong’s 5384), usually translated <char style="it">love</char>,
        sometimes means <char style="it">kiss </char>or <char style="it">friend.</char></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[H]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[H]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">caress my head with lotion</char>…<char style="it">cover my feet with special oil</char>…Lit:
        <char style="it">anoint my head with oil…anoint my feet with myrrh</char>. Myrrh is much more expensive
        than oil. Ref. note of Matt. 6:17 for anointing with oil.</char>
    </note>
