  <chapter number="10" style="c" sid="LUK 10" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 10:1" />After these things <char style="it">happened</char>, the Lord appointed seventy-two others and sent them
        out in sets of twos as probes<char style="sup">[a]</char> into every city and place which he personally
        intended to visit. <verse eid="LUK 10:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 10:2" />He started <char style="it">his talk by</char> saying to them, <char style="wj">“The harvest is large
        indeed, but the workers are few. Therefore, ask the Harvest Chief if he would catapult workers out</char><char
        style="sup">[b]</char><char style="wj"> into his harvest— </char><verse eid="LUK 10:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 10:3" /><char style="wj">Get going!</char>
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 10:3"><char style="wj">“Take note: I’m sending you out like lambs in the midst of wolves. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:3"/>
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 10:4" /><char style="wj">Don’t carry a wallet, a travel pack, or sandals, and don’t take too kindly to anyone
        while on the road. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 10:5" /><char style="wj">Now, whatever house you happen to enter, first say, ‘</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">I
        offer</char></char><char style="wj"> peace to this house’ (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">i.e.,
        I extend my offer of friendship to all in this house and my willingness to get along with you</char></char><char
        style="wj">). </char><verse eid="LUK 10:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 10:6" /><char style="wj">If there happens to be a son of peace there (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">i.e.,
        if the leader of the house willingly and joyfully engages in friendships and will gets along well with
        people</char></char><char style="wj">), your offer of piece will stick. Otherwise, it’ll bounce back
        to you</char><char style="sup">[A]</char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 10:7" /><char style="wj">Stay in that very house, eating and drinking that which they have on hand; you see,
        the worker is entitled to his wage</char><char style="sup">[c]</char><char style="wj">. Don’t hop from
        house to house. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 10:8" /><char style="wj">If you happen to go into a city and they receive you—whole-heartedly welcome you and
        embrace your ministry—eat those things which are put in front of you.</char><verse eid="LUK 10:8" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 10:9" /><char style="wj">”Heal those in </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">the city </char></char><char
        style="wj">who are rundown with an illness of some sort and say to them, ‘God’s involvement with mankind
        (God’s kingdom) is here and now and within reach</char><char style="sup">[d]</char><char style="wj">.’
        </char><verse eid="LUK 10:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 10:10" /><char style="wj">But should you go into a city and they won’t receive you, on your way out, make a statement
        in its town squares and on its boulevards, </char><verse eid="LUK 10:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 10:11" /><char style="wj">and wipe off the dust from the city that’s clinging to your feet </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">symbolic of you being through with them</char></char><char style="wj">. In any event, understand
        this, that God’s kingdom is here and now and within reach. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 10:12" /><char style="wj">Mark my words: on That Day, it will be more tolerable for Sodom than for that city.</char><verse eid="LUK 10:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 10:13" /><char style="wj">”You’re in deep trouble, Chorazin! You’re in deep trouble Bethsaida! Because if the
        miracles which occurred among you had happened in Tyre and Sidon, those cities would’ve done the burlap-and-ashes
        thing</char><char style="sup">[B]</char><char style="wj"> and had a change of heart and of conduct</char><char
        style="sup">[e]</char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 10:14" /><char style="wj">In any event, on That Day, it will be more tolerable for Tyre and Sidon than for you.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 10:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 10:15" /><char style="wj">As for you, Capernaum,</char>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 10:15"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 10:15"><char style="wj">“You won’t be elevated all the way to heaven</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 10:15"><char style="wj">You will descend all the way to hell</char><verse eid="LUK 10:15"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 10:16" /><char style="wj">”He who listens to you listens to me, and he who disregards you disregards me, and he
        who disregards me disregards the One who sent me.”</char><verse eid="LUK 10:16" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 10:17" />The seventy-two returned full of joy saying, “Lord, even the demons obey us when we act using your delegated
        authority<char style="sup">[f]</char>.” <verse eid="LUK 10:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 10:18" />He said to them, <char style="wj">“Time and time again I saw, like a lightning strike, a demon get ejected
        from his spiritual dominion.</char><char style="sup">[C]</char><char style="wj"> </char><verse eid="LUK 10:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 10:19" /><char style="wj">Realize this: I have given you the authority to walk over serpents and scorpions, and
        over all the power of the enemy, and nothing will harm you, not even a bit. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 10:20" /><char style="wj">However, don’t get too excited about the fact that they obey you, but rejoice that you
        have clout in the spiritual world</char><char style="sup">[g]</char><char style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="LUK 10:20" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 10:21" />At that moment he was filled with rapture in the Holy Spirit<char style="sup">[h]</char> and said, <char
        style="wj">“I pour my heart out in confession to you, Father, Lord of heaven and earth, that you hid
        these things from the wise and intelligent and revealed them to children. Yes indeed, Father, </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">I am enraptured</char></char><char style="wj"> because the way things turned
        out is to please Your intense and profound scrutiny</char><char style="sup">[i]</char><char style="wj">.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 10:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 10:22" /><char style="wj">All things have been given to me by my Father, and no one knows who or what the son
        is except the Father, and who or what the Father is except for the son and </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">except for </char></char><char style="wj">whomever the son might choose to reveal it to.”
        </char><verse eid="LUK 10:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 10:23" /><char style="wj">He turned and faced the disciples and said to them alone, “Blessed be the eyes that
        see what you see. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 10:24" /><char style="wj">I’ll tell you this much: many prophets and kings desired to see those things which you
        see and didn’t </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">get to </char></char><char style="wj">see </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">them</char></char><char style="wj">, and to hear those things which you heard
        and didn’t </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">get to </char></char><char style="wj">hear </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">them</char></char><char style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="LUK 10:24" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 10:25" />As chance would have it, some expert in the Law of Moses stood up and put him on the spot saying,
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 10:25">“Teacher, what must one do to legitimately claim and lay hold of<char style="sup">[D]</char> that special
        fullness of life (eternal life<char style="sup">[E]</char>)?”<verse eid="LUK 10:25"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 10:26" />He said to him, <char style="wj">“What’s been established in writing and thereby decreed</char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj"> </char></char><char style="wj">by the Law </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">of Moses</char></char><char style="wj">?”</char><verse eid="LUK 10:26" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 10:27" />His response to him was, “’You shall love the Lord your God from out of your entire heart, with your
        entire mind, will, and emotions<char style="sup">[j]</char>, with your entire ability and might, and
        with your entire intellect.’ Also, ‘<char style="it">You shall love </char>your neighbor as yourself.’”<verse eid="LUK 10:27" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 10:28" />He said, <char style="wj">“You answered correctly. Do this and you shall have </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">eternal</char></char><char style="wj"> life</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="LUK 10:28" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 10:29" />But wanting to vindicate (or exculpate) himself, he said to Jesus, “So who is my neighbor?”<verse eid="LUK 10:29" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 10:30" />Jesus formulated<char style="sup">[l]</char> <char style="it">a reply for him</char>: <char style="wj">“There
        was a certain man who was heading to Jericho from Jerusalem, and robbers jumped him, stripped him </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">of everything of value</char></char><char style="wj">, beat him up, and left
        him there half-dead. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 10:31" /><char style="wj">By chance, some priest was on that </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">very </char></char><char
        style="wj">road heading in the same direction</char><char style="sup">[m]</char><char style="wj">, and
        when he saw him passed by him on the opposite side of the road. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 10:32" /><char style="wj">A local clergyman</char><char style="sup">[n]</char><char style="wj"> came too, and
        when he saw him, likewise passed by him on the opposite side of the road. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="LUK 10:33" /><char style="wj">But someone who was travelling—a Samaritan—ran across him, and when he saw him felt
        deeply sorry for him. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="LUK 10:34" /><char style="wj">He came and dressed his wounds, applying lotion and disinfectant</char><char style="sup">[o]</char><char
        style="wj">, put him on his own donkey, led him to an inn, and took care of him. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="LUK 10:35" /><char style="wj">The next day he handed the innkeeper cash for a couple weeks’ stay</char><char style="sup">[p]</char><char
        style="wj"> and said, ‘Look after him. If his bill happens to run over, I personally will pay you back
        on the return trip.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 10:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="LUK 10:36" /><char style="wj">Which one of these three do you suppose had succeeded in becoming a neighbor to the
        one who got jumped by the robbers?”</char> <verse eid="LUK 10:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="LUK 10:37" />He said, “The one who had pity on him.” Jesus said to him, <char style="wj">“Go and do the same.”</char><verse eid="LUK 10:37" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="LUK 10:38" />While they were travelling about, he himself <char style="it">and not just his disciples </char>entered
        a certain town. A woman named Martha was entertaining him, <verse eid="LUK 10:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="LUK 10:39" />and this woman had a sister named Mary, who moreover was sitting near the Lord attentively<char style="sup">[q]</char>,
        listening on and on to his message. <verse eid="LUK 10:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="LUK 10:40" />But Martha was constantly being distracted by what was involved in the preparations and waiting on everyone.
        She went straight up to him<char style="sup">[r]</char> and said, “Lord, don’t you care that my sister
        has left me with all the work<char style="sup">[s]</char>? So now, say something to her to get her to
        help out.” <verse eid="LUK 10:40" />
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="LUK 10:41" />His response to her was, <char style="wj">“Martha, Martha, you worry about so many things and get upset
        about them. </char><verse eid="LUK 10:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="LUK 10:42" /><char style="it"><char style="wj">To choose</char></char><char style="wj"> </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">the</char></char><char style="wj"> one </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">good </char></char><char
        style="wj">thing is what’s needed. You see, Mary </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">considered
        her options and</char></char><char style="wj"> made the best choice; the very thing </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">she chose</char></char><char style="wj"> will not be taken away from her.</char><char style="sup">[F]</char><char
        style="wj">”</char><verse eid="LUK 10:42" />
    </para>
