    <note caller="[a]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[a]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">as probes</char>…Lit: <char style="it">before his face</char>. A common idiom; ref.
        note of Luke 9:52.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[b]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[b]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">catapult workers out</char>…Lit: <char style="it">cast workers out</char></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[c]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[c]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">the worker is entitled to his wage</char>…Or: <char style="it">the worker is worthy
        of his keep. </char>A phrase used repeatedly throughout the NT, originating in the Law of Moses, a principle
        well-known to all Jews.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[d]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[d]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">God’s kingdom is here and now and within reach</char>…Lit: <char style="it">God’s kingdom
        has come near you</char></char>
    </note>
