  <chapter number="11" style="c" sid="LUK 11" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 11:1" />He happened to be praying somewhere, and just as he finished one of his disciples said to him, “Lord,
        teach<char style="sup">[a]</char> us how to pray, just as John taught his disciples.” <verse eid="LUK 11:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 11:2" />He said to them, <char style="wj">“When you pray, say,</char>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:2"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:2"><char style="wj">“Father, may You be revered for who You are</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:2"><char style="wj">And for Your reputation</char><char style="sup">[b]</char><char style="wj">.</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:2"><char style="wj">Have Your involvement with us (Your kingdom) come.</char><verse eid="LUK 11:2"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 11:3" /><char style="wj">Give us a meal ticket each day.</char><verse eid="LUK 11:3" />
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 11:4" /><char style="wj">Forgive our sins.</char>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:4"><char style="wj">You see, we, for our part, also forgive everyone</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:4"><char style="wj">Who has a negative score on our scorecard</char><char style="sup">[c]</char><char style="wj">.</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:4"><char style="wj">May you not transport us to temptation—</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:4"><char style="wj">Temptations and trials that would break us.”</char><verse eid="LUK 11:4"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 11:5" /><char style="wj">He said to them, “All of you probably have a friend like this, someone you were to go
        to in the middle of the night and say, ‘Hey good buddy, I need to borrow three loaves of bread, </char><verse eid="LUK 11:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 11:6" /><char style="wj">since my friend was on the road and stopped by </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">unexpectedly</char></char><char
        style="wj">, and I don’t have anything to put on the table,’ </char><verse eid="LUK 11:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 11:7" /><char style="wj">and good-old-so-and-so there on the inside replies, ‘Don’t bother me. I’m locked up
        for the night, and my children are all tucked in</char><char style="sup">[A]</char><char style="wj">;
        I can’t get up to get you </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">something.</char></char><char style="wj">’</char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj"> </char></char><verse eid="LUK 11:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 11:8" /><char style="wj">I’m telling you, even if he won’t get up because he’s your friend, he sure will get
        up because of your relentlessness and give you anything you need. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 11:9" /><char style="wj">This is me talking now—ask, and it will be given to you; seek and you will find; knock,
        and it will be opened for you. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 11:10" /><char style="wj">You see, everyone who asks receives, who seeks finds, who knocks gets doors opened.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 11:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 11:11" /><char style="wj">Can you think of any father you know of whose son asks him for a fish and gives him
        a snake instead of a fish? </char><verse eid="LUK 11:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 11:12" /><char style="wj">Or for an egg and gives him a scorpion? </char><verse eid="LUK 11:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 11:13" /><char style="wj">So now, if the lying, cheating, stealing, selfish, etc. people</char><char style="sup">[d]</char><char
        style="wj"> out there have the sense to give good gifts to their children, how much more will the Father
        give from heaven above a spirit which is indeed the Holy Spirit to those asking Him</char><char style="sup">[B]</char><char
        style="wj">?”</char><verse eid="LUK 11:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 11:14" />He was <char style="it">in the middle of</char> casting out a deaf demon (<char style="it">i.e. a demon
        of deafness</char>)<char style="sup">[C]</char>, and it so happened that when the demon left, the deaf
        man spoke. The crowd was amazed. <verse eid="LUK 11:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 11:15" />But some of them said, “He casts out demons by the head demon himself, Beelzebub.” <verse eid="LUK 11:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 11:16" />But others, testing him in order to expose a fault, time and time again were trying to get him to perform
        a spectacular miracle<char style="sup">[e]</char>. <verse eid="LUK 11:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 11:17" />He, though, cognizant of the inclination behind their thoughts, said to them, <char style="wj">“Every
        kingdom split into factions which are pitted against each another</char><char style="sup">[f]</char><char
        style="wj"> will fall into oblivion, and an organization pitted against the organization </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">itself </char></char><char style="wj">will fall. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 11:18" /><char style="wj">Now if Satan’s </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">dominion</char></char><char
        style="sup">[g]</char><char style="wj"> is also divided into factions pitted against each other, how
        will his kingdom maintain working order</char><char style="sup">[h]</char><char style="wj">, seeing that
        you claim that I’m casting out demons with the assistance of Beelzebub? </char><verse eid="LUK 11:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 11:19" /><char style="wj">So if what I’m doing on my end is casting out demons by using Beelzebub’s assistance,
        with whose assistance do your protégés</char><char style="sup">[i]</char><char style="wj"> cast out demons</char><char
        style="sup">[D]</char><char style="wj">? By means of this </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">dilemma</char></char><char
        style="wj">, what they do on their end will determine whether you’re right or wrong </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">about your claim</char></char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 11:20" /><char style="wj">Now if I’m casting out the demons by The Touch of God</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char
        style="wj">, then God’s involvement with mankind (God’s kingdom) is here-and-now and in your face</char><char
        style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj">.</char><verse eid="LUK 11:20" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 11:21" /><char style="wj">”When a man who’s armed to the hilt</char><char style="sup">[E]</char><char style="wj">
        guards his own fenced-in property, keeping an eye on it at all times, his possessions remain undisturbed.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 11:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 11:22" /><char style="wj">As soon as a man more powerful than him assaults him and subdues him, he confiscates
        the </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">weapons and</char></char><char style="wj"> armor</char><char
        style="sup">[E]</char><char style="wj"> upon which he had relied and distributes his possessions </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">to his partners in crime</char></char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 11:23" /><char style="wj">Whoever or whatever is not with me is against me, and whoever or whatever’s not contributing
        to my cause detracts from it</char><char style="sup">[m]</char><char style="wj">.</char><verse eid="LUK 11:23" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 11:24" /><char style="wj">”When the archetypical filthy, disgusting spirit leaves a person, it goes throughout
        places which are uninhabitable or inhospitable</char><char style="sup">[n]</char><char style="wj">, seeking
        a place to take a break or to settle in, at least for a little while,</char><char style="sup">[o]</char><char
        style="wj"> and doesn’t find any.</char><char style="sup">[F]</char><char style="wj"> Then it says, ‘I’ll
        go back and reenter my home, </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">the domicile</char></char><char
        style="wj"> from where I left.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 11:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 11:25" /><char style="wj">It comes and finds that it’s been all tidied up and that everything’s been put back
        in order. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 11:26" /><char style="wj">Then it goes and takes with it a complete set of other spirits</char><char style="sup">[p]</char><char
        style="wj">, ones more evil than itself, and they enter and take up residency there, and that poor</char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj"> </char></char><char style="wj">guy ends up being in worse shape than when
        he started.”</char><verse eid="LUK 11:26" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 11:27" />It so happened that, when he was in the middle of saying these things, a woman lifted her voice over
        the crowd, “Blessed be the womb that carried you <char style="it">through pregnancy</char> and the breast
        that breast-fed you.” <verse eid="LUK 11:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 11:28" />He, though, said, <char style="wj">“On the contrary—blessed be those who hear God’s word and guard and
        watch over it in order to keep it.”</char><verse eid="LUK 11:28" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 11:29" />As the crowd built up more and more, he proceeded to say, <char style="wj">“This prevailing Zeitgeist</char><char
        style="sup">[q]</char><char style="wj"> in particular is one of evil. It seeks a spectacular miracle,
        but none such will be given to it except for Jonah’s miracle. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 11:30" /><char style="wj">You see, just as Jonah became a sign </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">from God</char></char><char
        style="wj"> to the Ninevites, in the same way the Man</char><char style="sup">[r]</char><char style="wj">
        too will be </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">a similar type of sign from God</char></char><char
        style="wj"> to those adhering to this Zeitgeist. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 11:31" /><char style="wj">The Queen of Sheba will be called to testify on Judgment Day taking a stand and confronting
        the men who adhere to this Zeitgeist</char><char style="sup">[s]</char><char style="wj"> and will condemn
        them </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">with her testimony</char></char><char style="wj">, because
        she came from the other side of the planet to hear Solomon’s wisdom, and, take note of this: something
        greater than Solomon is in this very place. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 11:32" /><char style="wj">The men of Nineveh will be called to testify on Judgment Day and will take a stand and
        confront this Zeitgeist and those who adhere to it and will condemn it </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">with their testimony</char></char><char style="wj">, because they had a change of heart and
        mended their ways because of Jonah’s preaching, and take note of this: something greater than Jonah is
        in this very place.</char><verse eid="LUK 11:32" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="LUK 11:33" /><char style="wj">”No one who has lit a lamp places it in the cellar or under a basket but instead </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">places it </char></char><char style="wj">upon the lampstand so that it provides
        light for those entering. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="LUK 11:34" /><char style="wj">Your eye (</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">i.e., what’s got your attention and
        you’re fascinated with</char></char><char style="wj">) is your body’s source of light, its lamp. When
        your eye can see clearly, your entire body becomes illuminated also. When it sees poorly (</char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">i.e., when you’re fixated on bad things</char></char><char style="wj">),
        your body becomes dark also. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="LUK 11:35" /><char style="wj">So now, see to it that the light in you not </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">in
        fact </char></char><char style="wj">be darkness. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="LUK 11:36" /><char style="wj">So now, if your entire body is filled with light, not having any part of it which is
        dark, it will be illuminated entirely like when the typical lamp by its sheer brightness illuminates
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">everything around</char></char><char style="wj"> you.”</char><verse eid="LUK 11:36" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="LUK 11:37" />During the talk, the Pharisees asked him if he would dine with them, so he entered <char style="it">the
        house where the dinner was being held </char>and had a seat at the table<char style="sup">[t]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 11:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="LUK 11:38" />Seeing this, the Pharisees were stunned because he hadn’t first been immersed in water before the meal.<verse eid="LUK 11:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="LUK 11:39" />The Lord said to them, <char style="wj">“Right around now</char><char style="sup">[G]</char><char style="wj">,
        you Pharisees—you clean the outside of the cup and the dish, but your insides are filled to the brim
        with avarice</char><char style="sup">[H]</char><char style="wj"> and iniquity. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="LUK 11:40" /><char style="wj">Stupid people. Didn’t He who made the outside </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">of
        the cup </char></char><char style="wj">also make the inside? </char><verse eid="LUK 11:40" />
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="LUK 11:41" /><char style="wj">Just give away what’s on the inside </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">like you’re
        giving</char></char><char style="wj"> a gift to charity, and—presto—you can handle anything that’s off-limits
        from a ritualistic perspective.</char><char style="sup">[I]</char><char style="wj">”</char><verse eid="LUK 11:41" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="LUK 11:42" /><char style="wj">”Enough of that—you’re in for it Pharisees, because you donate a small percentage of
        your</char><char style="sup">[u]</char><char style="wj"> mint and rue and of every herb imaginable, and
        overlook or flat-out ignore the judgment and the love of God; you know you’re supposed to do these things,
        but those things don’t </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">seem to</char></char><char style="wj">
        materialize. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:42" />
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="LUK 11:43" /><char style="wj">You’re in for it Pharisees, because you love the seats of honor in the synagogues and
        the greetings in the marketplace and town-square. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:43" />
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="LUK 11:44" /><char style="wj">You’re in for it, because you are like the Out-of-Sight-Tombs: the people who walk over
        top of them are unaware of them.”</char><verse eid="LUK 11:44" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="LUK 11:45" />One of the experts in the Law of Moses<char style="sup">[v]</char> <char style="it">then </char>retorts,
        “Teacher, these words insult us as well.” <verse eid="LUK 11:45" />
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="LUK 11:46" />Jesus said, “<char style="wj">You’re in for it too, you Law experts, because you saddle people with burdens
        that are too great to bear; you, meanwhile, won’t even lift a finger to attempt to bear</char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj"> </char></char><char style="wj">the same burden. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:46" />
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="LUK 11:47" /><char style="wj">You’re in for it, because you erect the prophets’ tombs, but </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">it was</char></char><char style="wj"> your predecessors</char><char style="sup">[w]</char><char
        style="wj"> </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">who</char></char><char style="wj"> </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">were the ones who</char></char><char style="wj"> killed them. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:47" />
      <verse number="48" style="v" sid="LUK 11:48" /><char style="wj">Consequently, you affirm</char><char style="sup">[x]</char><char style="wj"> and approve
        of your predecessors’ actions, because they on the one hand killed them, but you on the other hand erect
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">tombs in the prophets’ memory. </char></char><verse eid="LUK 11:48" />
      <verse number="49" style="v" sid="LUK 11:49" /><char style="wj">For this reason, God in His wisdom</char><char style="sup">[y]</char><char style="wj">
        said,</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:49"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:49"><char style="wj">“I’ll send prophets and missionaries</char><char style="sup">[z]</char><char style="wj">
        to you,</char>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:49"><char style="wj">And you will kill and persecute</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 11:49"><char style="it"><char style="wj">Select ones</char></char><char style="wj"> from among them</char><verse eid="LUK 11:49"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="50" style="v" sid="LUK 11:50" /><char style="wj">”…Resulting in those adhering to this Zeitgeist being held accountable for</char><char
        style="sup">[aa]</char><char style="wj"> the blood of all the prophets which has been poured out since
        the dawn of civilization, </char><verse eid="LUK 11:50" />
      <verse number="51" style="v" sid="LUK 11:51" /><char style="wj">from the blood of Abel all the way to the blood of Zechariah, who perished between the
        altar and the temple itself. Yes indeed, I’m telling you what, those who adhere to this prevailing Zeitgeist
        will be held accountable for it. </char><verse eid="LUK 11:51" />
      <verse number="52" style="v" sid="LUK 11:52" /><char style="wj">You’re in for it, experts, because you took away the key of knowledge; you, as far as
        your own selves are concerned, won’t join in</char><char style="sup">[bb]</char><char style="wj"> </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">with knowledge</char></char><char style="wj">, and you forbid or otherwise
        hinder those in the process of joining.”</char><verse eid="LUK 11:52" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="53" style="v" sid="LUK 11:53" />After he left <char style="it">the house</char>, from there on out, the experts in the Law and the Pharisees
        held a terrible grudge against him, and over and over tried to get him to make off-the-cuff remarks,
        questioning him about many things, <verse eid="LUK 11:53" />
      <verse number="54" style="v" sid="LUK 11:54" />plotting in order to catch him in something <char style="it">which he </char>blurted out of his mouth
        <char style="it">which was wrong</char>.<verse eid="LUK 11:54" />
    </para>
