    <note caller="[a]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[a]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">in the forefront of God’s mind</char>…Lit: <char style="it">before God</char>. A common
        OT phrase.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[b]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[b]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">the Man</char>…Lit: <char style="it">the Son of Man</char>. Ref. note of Matt 8:20.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[c]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[c]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">any sort of</char>…Lit: <char style="it">all. </char>This is a figure of speech called
        a synecdoche and is similar to the words <char style="it">all evil </char>in 1 Tim. 6:10, <char style="it">the
        love of money is the root of all evil.</char></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[d]" style="f">
