  <chapter number="14" style="c" sid="LUK 14" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 14:1" />He happened to go to the house of some high-up Pharisee for a meal<char style="sup">[a]</char> on the
        Sabbath, and they were watching every step that he made. <verse eid="LUK 14:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 14:2" />As it turned out, somebody there right in front of him was afflicted with dropsy. <verse eid="LUK 14:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 14:3" />Jesus thought a bit and said to the experts in the Law of Moses<char style="sup">[b]</char> and to the
        Pharisees, <char style="wj">“Is one allowed or not allowed to heal on the Sabbath?”</char> <verse eid="LUK 14:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 14:4" />They kept silent. He laid hold of him, healed him, and let him go. <verse eid="LUK 14:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 14:5" />He said to them, <char style="wj">“Which one of you who owns a donkey or cow that falls into a well won’t
        pull him out right away if it’s on a Sabbath?” </char><verse eid="LUK 14:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 14:6" />They weren’t able to refute this.<verse eid="LUK 14:6" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 14:7" />He proceeded to tell an analogy to the guests, mindful of how the places of honor at the table, those
        seats reserved for the most important guests, were being considered and chosen. <verse eid="LUK 14:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 14:8" /><char style="wj">“When you happen to get invited by someone to a wedding, don’t take the seat of honor,
        lest some </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">other</char></char><char style="wj"> guest be regarded
        as more important than you, </char><verse eid="LUK 14:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 14:9" /><char style="wj">and the host has to say to you, ‘This place is taken’; and then you’ll be fixin’ to
        occupy</char><char style="sup">[c]</char><char style="wj"> the least prestigious place in humiliation.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 14:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 14:10" /><char style="wj">Instead, when you happen to get invited, go and seat yourself</char><char style="sup">[d]</char><char
        style="wj"> at the least prestigious place, so that when the host happens to come by, he’ll tell you,
        ‘Dear friend, upgrade to a more prestigious seat.’ Then it will be a cause for you </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">to receive</char></char><char style="wj"> adulation and congratulation in front of all the
        guests</char><char style="sup">[e]</char><char style="wj">, </char><verse eid="LUK 14:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 14:11" /><char style="wj">because all who exalt themselves will be abased and those who abase themselves will
        be exalted.”</char><verse eid="LUK 14:11" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 14:12" />He proceeded to speak to the guests, <char style="wj">“When you happen to host a luncheon or a dinner,
        don’t invite your close friends, your brothers and sisters, your relatives, or your rich neighbors, lest
        they also choose to reciprocate, and it becomes self-benefiting to you. </char><verse eid="LUK 14:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 14:13" /><char style="wj">Instead, when you host a reception, invite the poor, the crippled, the lame, the blind…
        </char><verse eid="LUK 14:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 14:14" /><char style="wj">And it’ll be a blessing, because they won’t have anything to pay you back with. You
        see, your compensation will be in the life-to-come of those who are right with God</char><char style="sup">[f]</char><char
        style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="LUK 14:14" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 14:15" />Upon hearing these things, one of the fellow guests said to him, “Blessed be whoever has a meal<char
        style="sup">[a]</char> while a participant in God’s plan (in God’s kingdom).” <verse eid="LUK 14:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 14:16" />He said to him, <char style="wj">“Some man threw a huge dinner feast and invited many people. </char><verse eid="LUK 14:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 14:17" /><char style="wj">At the start of the dinner, he sent his servant and said to those invited,</char>
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 14:17"><char style="wj">“’Come, everything’s ready’.” </char><verse eid="LUK 14:17"/>
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 14:18" /><char style="wj">They began to make excuses, one after another.</char>
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 14:18"><char style="wj">“The first said to him, ‘I bought a field, and I have to go out and look it over. I
        ask to be excused.’</char><verse eid="LUK 14:18"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 14:19" /><char style="wj">”Another said, ‘I bought five oxen yokes, and I’m going out to inspect them. I ask to
        be excused.’</char><verse eid="LUK 14:19" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 14:20" /><char style="wj">”Another said, ‘I got married</char><char style="sup">[g]</char><char style="wj">, and
        because of that, I won’t be able to make it.’</char><verse eid="LUK 14:20" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 14:21" /><char style="wj">”After making the rounds, the servant told his boss these things. Then the one sponsoring
        and hosting the event</char><char style="sup">[h]</char><char style="wj"> became furious and said to
        his servant, ‘Quickly now—go to the boulevards and alleys in the city and to the poor, crippled, blind,
        and lame and direct them here.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 14:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 14:22" /><char style="wj">The servant said, ‘Boss, I did what you told me to, and there’s still empty places.’
        </char><verse eid="LUK 14:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 14:23" /><char style="wj">The boss said to the servant, ‘Go out to the highways and interstates</char><char style="sup">[i]</char><char
        style="wj"> and make them come, so that my hall</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char style="wj"> would
        be filled. </char><verse eid="LUK 14:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 14:24" /><char style="wj">I’ll tell you this much: not a single one of those people who were invited will taste
        even a morsel of my dinner’.”</char><verse eid="LUK 14:24" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 14:25" />Large crowds gathered around him, and he addressed them. <verse eid="LUK 14:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 14:26" /><char style="wj">”If someone comes to me and doesn’t have complete disregard for</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char
        style="wj"> his own father, mother, wife, children, brothers, and sisters, and even more his own life-being,
        can’t be my disciple. </char><verse eid="LUK 14:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 14:27" /><char style="wj">Whoever won’t bear his own cross</char><char style="sup">[A]</char><char style="wj">
        and follow in my footsteps</char><char style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj"> can’t be my disciple.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 14:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 14:28" /><char style="wj">To the point, show me a person who wants to construct a tower who doesn’t sit down at
        a chair ahead of time and calculate the cost, to see if he has enough to complete </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">the project</char></char><char style="wj">, </char><verse eid="LUK 14:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 14:29" /><char style="wj">lest he lay the foundation and not be able to complete everything? All the onlookers
        will begin to make fun of him </char><verse eid="LUK 14:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 14:30" /><char style="wj">saying, ‘That guy began construction but wasn’t able to bring things to completion.’
        </char><verse eid="LUK 14:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 14:31" /><char style="wj">Or, which king, who when maneuvering </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">his army</char></char><char
        style="wj"> encounters another king facing off to engage </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">him
        </char></char><char style="wj">in battle, won’t beforehand sit </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">at
        the table</char></char><char style="wj"> and hold council to see if with 10,000 </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">troops</char></char><char style="wj"> he can go head-to-head against 20,000 and win? </char><verse eid="LUK 14:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 14:32" /><char style="wj">But if it turns out that he can’t, while he’s still a good distance off, he’ll send
        a senior </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">officer</char></char><char style="wj"> to sue for peace.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 14:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="LUK 14:33" /><char style="wj">Consequently, it’s the same way: if there’s any one of you won’t part with all of his
        own possessions, he can’t be my disciple.</char><verse eid="LUK 14:33" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="LUK 14:34" /><char style="wj">”So now, the salt </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">source </char></char><char
        style="wj">works well</char><char style="sup">[B]</char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="LUK 14:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="LUK 14:35" /><char style="wj">It’s not suitable to be put in the ground nor in a compost pile</char><char style="sup">[m]</char><char
        style="wj">. It’ll be categorically rejected and get thrown out. A word to the wise is sufficient</char><char
        style="sup">[n]</char><char style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="LUK 14:35" />
    </para>
