  <!--   Chapter 15   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="15" style="c" sid="LUK 15" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 15:1" />All of the tax collectors and the sinners<char style="sup">[a]</char> were drawing near to him to listen
        to what he had to say. <verse eid="LUK 15:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 15:2" />The Pharisees and the designated teachers<char style="sup">[b]</char> wouldn’t stop grumbling and complaining,
        saying that this guy heartily welcomes<char style="sup">[c]</char> sinners and dines with them. <verse eid="LUK 15:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 15:3" />He told them this analogy, <verse eid="LUK 15:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 15:4" /><char style="wj">“Do you know anyone who owns a hundred sheep and has one of them go missing, who won’t
        leave the ninety-nine out in the middle of nowhere and go after the one that’s missing, </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">and won’t stop</char></char><char style="wj"> until he succeeds in finding
        it? </char><verse eid="LUK 15:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 15:5" /><char style="wj">When he finds it, while rejoicing he puts it on his shoulders. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 15:6" /><char style="wj">Once he gets back to his place, he’ll call his friends and neighbors over and say to
        them, ‘I’m so glad and excited I found my missing sheep. High-fives!</char><char style="sup">[d]</char><char
        style="wj">’ </char><verse eid="LUK 15:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 15:7" /><char style="wj">Let me tell you, in the same way there’ll be joy in heaven when one sinner changes his
        life to do right than for ninety-nine who are already doing right and have no need to make this change.</char><verse eid="LUK 15:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 15:8" /><char style="wj">”Or, do you know any woman who has ten $100 bills</char><char style="sup">[A]</char><char
        style="wj"> and one were to go missing, who won’t light a lamp and sweep the house and search carefully
        until she finds it? </char><verse eid="LUK 15:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 15:9" /><char style="wj">She finds it and calls her good friends and neighbors over and says, ‘I’m so glad and
        excited that I found the missing $100 bill. High-fives!’ </char><verse eid="LUK 15:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 15:10" /><char style="wj">Let me tell you, the joy that occurs in the presence of the angels</char><char style="sup">[B]</char><char
        style="wj"> when one sinner changes his life to do right is just like that.”</char><verse eid="LUK 15:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 15:11" /><char style="wj">He said, “A certain man had two sons, </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">and this
        is what he experienced with them</char></char><char style="sup">[e]</char><char style="wj">: </char><verse eid="LUK 15:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 15:12" /><char style="wj">The younger of them said to the father, ‘Father, give me my allotted share of the property.’
        So he distributed the estate among them. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 15:13" /><char style="wj">Over many days the younger son gathered everything up, then took a journey to a far-away
        country and recklessly squandered his share of the estate there. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 15:14" /><char style="wj">After wasting everything he owned, a severe famine occurred throughout that country,
        and it affected him personally, as he began to be in need.</char><verse eid="LUK 15:14" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 15:15" /><char style="wj">”He went and hired on with one of the landowners in that country, and he sent him to
        his grazing lands to feed pigs. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 15:16" /><char style="wj">He had an urge that wouldn’t quit to eat the feed which the pigs were eating; nobody
        was giving him </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">any food to eat</char></char><char style="wj">.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 15:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 15:17" /><char style="wj">He came to his senses and said, ‘How many of my father’s hired hands have more than
        enough food to eat</char><char style="sup">[f]</char><char style="wj">, but I, however, am wasting away
        from hunger here. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 15:18" /><char style="wj">I’ll pack up, go to my father, and say to him, “Father, I have sinned against God and
        ever so much against you;</char><char style="sup">[C]</char><char style="wj"> </char><verse eid="LUK 15:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 15:19" /><char style="wj">no longer am I worthy to be called your son. Treat me like I was one of your hired hands.”’
        </char><verse eid="LUK 15:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 15:20" /><char style="wj">And he packed up and went to his very-own father. But while yet still far off, keeping
        himself at a distance, hesitating apprehensively, his father saw him and was moved to compassion deep
        inside and ran and threw his arms around his neck</char><char style="sup">[g]</char><char style="wj">
        and kissed him fervently. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 15:21" /><char style="wj">The son said to him, ‘Father, I’ve sinned against God and ever so much against you;
        I’m no longer worthy to be called your son.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 15:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 15:22" /><char style="wj">The father said to his servants, ‘Quickly now, get out a Premier Robe</char><char style="sup">[D]</char><char
        style="wj">, bring it over here, and put it on him; and give him a ring for his finger and sandals for
        his feet, </char><verse eid="LUK 15:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 15:23" /><char style="wj">and get the fatted calf, slaughter it: we’re going to have a feast-celebration, </char><verse eid="LUK 15:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 15:24" /><char style="wj">because this son of mine was dead and came back to life, he was lost and has been found.
        And they began to celebrate.</char><verse eid="LUK 15:24" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 15:25" /><char style="wj">”Now his older son was out in the fields. As he was drawing near to the house, he heard
        music and dancing, </char><verse eid="LUK 15:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 15:26" /><char style="wj">He summoned one of the younger servants and started inquiring what these things could
        possibly be. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 15:27" /><char style="wj">He said to him, ‘It’s because your brother has come, and your father has slaughtered
        the fatted calf, since he received him back in good health.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 15:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 15:28" /><char style="wj">He became enraged and didn’t want to go in, so his father went out and asked him nicely.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 15:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 15:29" /><char style="wj">He responded to his father, ‘Look—for many years now I’ve been your servant and not
        a single time have I neglected </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">to obey a single</char></char><char
        style="wj"> command of yours, and you’ve never </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">even </char></char><char
        style="wj">given </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">me </char></char><char style="wj">a young goat
        so that I could celebrate with my friends. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 15:30" /><char style="wj">When this son of yours—who gobbled up your estate </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">spending
        it</char></char><char style="wj"> on prostitutes—came, you slaughtered the fatted calf for him.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 15:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 15:31" /><char style="wj">So he said to him, ‘Son, you always have been and always will be with me</char><char
        style="sup">[h]</char><char style="wj">, and everything I own is yours</char><char style="sup">[E]</char><char
        style="wj">. </char><verse eid="LUK 15:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 15:32" /><char style="wj">But we just had to celebrate and rejoice, since this brother of yours was dead and came
        to life, was lost and was found.’”</char><verse eid="LUK 15:32" />
    </para>
