  <!--   Chapter 20   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="20" style="c" sid="LUK 20" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 20:1" />On one of those days, while he happened to be teaching and proclaiming good news<char style="sup">[a]</char>
        to the folk-people in the temple, the chief priests and designated teachers<char style="sup">[b]</char>
        together with the <char style="it">head-council’s</char> councilmen approached him, trying to intimidate
        him, <verse eid="LUK 20:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 20:2" />saying, “By what authority do you do these things? In other words, who was it who gave you this authority?—Tell
        us.” <verse eid="LUK 20:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 20:3" />He replied to them, <char style="wj">“I’ll answer you in just one sentence</char><char style="sup">[c]</char><char
        style="wj">, and then you’ll tell me </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">something in return</char></char><char
        style="wj">: </char><verse eid="LUK 20:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 20:4" /><char style="wj">John’s baptism…did it originate</char><char style="it"><char style="wj"> </char></char><char
        style="wj">from heaven or was it man-made</char><char style="sup">[d]</char><char style="wj">?”</char><verse eid="LUK 20:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 20:5" />They reasoned together amongst themselves, saying, ‘If we were to say, “from heaven,” he’ll say, “why
        didn’t you believe in him?” <verse eid="LUK 20:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 20:6" />But if we were to say “man-made,” all the folk will stone us to death; the fact is, they’re convinced
        that John is a prophet.’ <verse eid="LUK 20:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 20:7" />They answered that they didn’t know where <char style="it">it came</char> from. <verse eid="LUK 20:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 20:8" />Jesus said to them, <char style="wj">“Nor will I tell you by what authority I do these things.”</char><verse eid="LUK 20:8" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 20:9" />Now he began telling the folk this analogy: <char style="wj">“A certain man planted a vineyard</char><char
        style="sup">[A]</char><char style="wj"> and leased it to farmers and went on a journey for an extensive
        amount of time. </char><verse eid="LUK 20:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 20:10" /><char style="wj">When the season was right, he sent the farmers a servant, in order that they would give
        him </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">a percentage</char></char><char style="wj"> of what the
        vineyard yielded. But the farmers beat him and sent him away empty-handed. </char><verse eid="LUK 20:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 20:11" /><char style="wj">In addition to this, he went the extra step to send a different servant. But they beat
        that fellow too. Dishonored </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">in this way</char></char><char style="wj">,
        they sent him away empty-handed. </char><verse eid="LUK 20:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 20:12" /><char style="wj">In addition, he went the extra step to send a third, but they hurt that fellow badly</char><char
        style="sup">[e]</char><char style="wj"> and drove him out as well. </char><verse eid="LUK 20:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 20:13" /><char style="wj">The vineyard owner said, ‘What am I going to do </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">about
        this</char></char><char style="wj">?—I’ll send my Beloved Son. Surely they’ll respect this </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">messenger</char></char><char style="wj">.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 20:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 20:14" /><char style="wj">Seeing him, the farmers thought the situation through with one another saying, ‘This
        fellow is the heir: let’s kill him, so that the inheritance would default to us,’ </char><verse eid="LUK 20:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 20:15" /><char style="wj">and they threw him out of the vineyard and killed him. What, now, will the vineyard
        owner do to them?— </char><verse eid="LUK 20:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 20:16" /><char style="wj">He’ll come and wipe those farmers out and lease the vineyard to others.”</char> Once
        they heard this, they said, “Heaven forbid!<char style="sup">[f]</char>” <verse eid="LUK 20:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 20:17" />He looked at them and said, <char style="wj">“So now, what about this verse of Scripture</char><char
        style="sup">[g]</char><char style="wj">:</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 20:17"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 20:17"><char style="wj">“A rock which the inspectors inspected and rejected:</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 20:17"><char style="wj">This is the one that became the main cornerstone</char><verse eid="LUK 20:17"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 20:18" /><char style="wj">”Everyone falling upon that stone will be crumbled; whoever it happens to fall on, it
        will pulverize.</char><char style="sup">[B]</char><char style="wj">”</char><verse eid="LUK 20:18" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 20:19" />At that moment, the designated teachers and chief priests sought to lay their hands upon him, but they
        feared the folk, seeing that they knew that he targeted them when he spoke that analogy.<verse eid="LUK 20:19" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 20:20" />On the lookout for an opportunity, they sent agents pretending to be honest, decent people, in order
        that they might trap him in something he said, so that he could be taken into custody by the chief <char
        style="it">priest </char>and <char style="it">placed </char>in the jurisdiction of the governor. <verse eid="LUK 20:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 20:21" />They asked him, “Teacher, we know that you’re straight-up when you speak and teach and that you’re not
        prone to partiality—not even close—you teach the exact truth of God’s way.”<verse eid="LUK 20:21" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 20:22" />”Do we have to pay taxes to Caesar or don’t we?”<verse eid="LUK 20:22" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 20:23" />Aware of their cunning, he said to them, <verse eid="LUK 20:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 20:24" /><char style="wj">”Show me a coin (a denarius</char><char style="sup">[C]</char><char style="wj">)…Who’s
        the image and inscription of?”</char></para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 20:24">They said, “Caesar.”<verse eid="LUK 20:24"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 20:25" />He said to them, <char style="wj">“So then, give all-things Caesar to Caesar and all-things God to God.”</char><verse eid="LUK 20:25" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 20:26" />They weren’t capable enough to trap him in any of his statements in front of the folk, and <char style="it">being
        </char>in awe of his answer, <char style="it">they </char>kept silent.<verse eid="LUK 20:26" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 20:27" />Some of the Sadducees (those who say there is no life after death<char style="sup">[h]</char>) approached
        him and asked, <verse eid="LUK 20:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 20:28" />”Teacher, Moses wrote <char style="it">in the Old Testament</char>, ‘If a man who has brothers and who
        has a wife dies childless, his brother should take the woman as his own wife and with his <char style="it">brother’s
        </char>wife sire and raise a <char style="it">bloodline</char> descendent. <verse eid="LUK 20:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 20:29" />Now there were seven brothers. The first got married and died childless. <verse eid="LUK 20:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 20:30" />The second <verse eid="LUK 20:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 20:31" />and the third also married her, etc., up to the seventh, who died without leaving a child. <verse eid="LUK 20:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 20:32" />Last of all, the woman died. <verse eid="LUK 20:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="LUK 20:33" />In the life-to-come, which of them will find himself married? The fact is, all seven had been married
        to her <char style="it">at one time</char>.”<verse eid="LUK 20:33" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="LUK 20:34" />Jesus said to them, <char style="wj">“Those who go with the flow in this present age</char><char style="sup">[i]</char><char
        style="wj"> go about getting married, </char><verse eid="LUK 20:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="LUK 20:35" /><char style="wj">but those deemed worthy of attaining that </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">blissful
        </char></char><char style="wj">age </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">to come</char></char><char
        style="wj">—life after death, don’t you know</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char style="wj">:</char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj"> escape from the frailty and corruption of this earthly body</char></char><char
        style="wj">—don’t go about getting married; </char><verse eid="LUK 20:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="LUK 20:36" /><char style="wj">you see, they can’t even die anymore, since they’re angel-like and are reflections of
        God’s nature</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char style="wj">, being products of the afterlife</char><char
        style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="LUK 20:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="LUK 20:37" /><char style="wj">And so, because there’s such a thing as life after death, at the </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">burning </char></char><char style="wj">bush Moses </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">when
        recording the incident as he was writing the Old Testament</char></char><char style="wj"> pointed this
        out as well, as he says, ‘The Lord God of Abraham and the God of Isaac and the God of Jacob.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 20:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="LUK 20:38" /><char style="wj">God isn’t </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">God </char></char><char style="wj">of
        those who are dead </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">and who therefore have ceased to exist</char></char><char
        style="wj">, but rather of those who are living </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">and therefore
        have not ceased to exist</char></char><char style="wj">, seeing that, to Him, all are living </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">and therefore still exist</char></char><char style="wj">.”</char> <verse eid="LUK 20:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="LUK 20:39" />Some of the designated teachers thought it over and replied, “Well-put, Teacher.” <verse eid="LUK 20:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="LUK 20:40" /><char style="wj">The fact of the matter is, they no longer dared ask him anything.</char><verse eid="LUK 20:40" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="LUK 20:41" /><char style="wj">He said to them, “How can people say that Christ, the Messiah, is David’s son?” </char><verse eid="LUK 20:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="LUK 20:42" /><char style="wj">The fact is, in the Book of Psalms David personally says,</char>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 20:42"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 20:42"><char style="wj">“A Lord said to my Lord</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 20:42"><char style="wj">Sit to the right of Me </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">as my right-hand man</char></char><verse eid="LUK 20:42"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi">
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="LUK 20:43" /><char style="wj">Until I decide to put your enemies under your subjugation</char><char style="sup">[m]</char><verse eid="LUK 20:43" />
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="LUK 20:44" /><char style="wj">”So now, David calls him ‘Lord’; how can he be his son?”</char><verse eid="LUK 20:44" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="LUK 20:45" />While all the folk were hearing this, he said to his disciples, <verse eid="LUK 20:45" />
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="LUK 20:46" /><char style="wj">”Beware of the designated teachers, those wanting to go about in robes, loving greetings
        in the marketplaces and town squares, loving the seats in the synagogue reserved for those who are important
        and the seats of honor at the </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">special </char></char><char style="wj">dinners.
        </char><verse eid="LUK 20:46" />
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="LUK 20:47" /><char style="wj">Those guys devour the homes of widows and </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">meanwhile
        </char></char><char style="wj">pray long-winded prayers to make themselves look good. Those guys will
        receive quite a harsh judgment.”</char><verse eid="LUK 20:47" />
    </para>
