  <!--   Chapter 23   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="23" style="c" sid="LUK 23" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 23:1" />The entire group of them got up and brought him to Pilate. <verse eid="LUK 23:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 23:2" />They proceeded to make accusations against him, saying, “We found this guy corrupting our culture, preventing
        people from paying Caesar taxes, and saying that he himself is a Messiah-king<char style="sup">[a]</char>.”<verse eid="LUK 23:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 23:3" />So Pilate asked him, “Are you the king of Jews?”, but he answered, <char style="wj">“</char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">Whatever</char></char><char style="wj"> you say</char><char style="sup">[b]</char><char style="wj">.”</char><verse eid="LUK 23:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 23:4" />Pilate said to the chief priests and to the throng, “I haven’t found anything to charge this man with,”<verse eid="LUK 23:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 23:5" />but they kept on saying more and more strenuously and assertively, “He incites the folk-people by teaching
        and instructing them throughout the whole <char style="it">district</char> of Judea. He started this
        in Galilee and <char style="it">worked his way</char> from there <char style="it">all the way down</char>
        to here.”<verse eid="LUK 23:5" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 23:6" />After Pilate heard <char style="it">this</char>, he asked if the man was a Galilean. <verse eid="LUK 23:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 23:7" />Once he realized that he falls under Herod’s jurisdiction, he sent him over to Herod, who was also in
        Jerusalem during these <char style="it">festival </char>days. <verse eid="LUK 23:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 23:8" />Seeing Jesus, Herod was especially delighted, since for quite a long time he’d been dying to see him
        owing to hearing about him time and time again, and <char style="it">with glee </char>was hoping to see
        him cause some supernatural sign or miracle to happen. <verse eid="LUK 23:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 23:9" />In a good deal of remarks and statements, he asked him <char style="it">several things</char>, but he
        wouldn’t reply. <verse eid="LUK 23:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 23:10" />The chief priests and the designated teachers<char style="sup">[c]</char> were standing there vehemently
        accusing him. <verse eid="LUK 23:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 23:11" />Herod and his soldiers together treated him with contempt, mocked him by dressing him in bright, colorful,
        beautiful clothing<char style="sup">[A]</char>, and sent him back to Pilate. <verse eid="LUK 23:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 23:12" />That very day a friendship formed between Herod and Pilate; hitherto they had been hostile towards each
        other.<verse eid="LUK 23:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 23:13" />Now Pilate summoned the chief priests, leaders, and the folk-people. <verse eid="LUK 23:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 23:14" />He said to them, “You brought me this man who supposedly subverts the folk, and—as you can see—I personally
        examined him in front of you all and found nothing to charge him with, <verse eid="LUK 23:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 23:15" />and—no—neither did Herod, seeing that he sent him back to us. And—as you can see—nothing worthy of death
        has been committed by him. <verse eid="LUK 23:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 23:16" />So now, I’ll teach him a lesson by flogging him and <char style="it">then </char>I’ll set him free.”<verse eid="LUK 23:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 23:17" /><char style="sup">[B]</char><verse eid="LUK 23:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 23:18" />They shouted back in unison, “Get rid of this guy and let Barabbas go for us.” <verse eid="LUK 23:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 23:19" />(This was the very person who was thrown in prison for murderer because of some insurrection which occurred
        in the city.)<verse eid="LUK 23:19" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 23:20" />Again, Pilate addressed them, “<char style="it">Are you </char>wanting to let Jesus go?”,<verse eid="LUK 23:20" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 23:21" />but they kept on shouting telling him, “Crucify <char style="it">him and</char> crucify him <char style="it">some
        more</char><char style="sup">[d]</char>!”<verse eid="LUK 23:21" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 23:22" />The third time he said to them, “Why? What has this guy done wrong? I’ve found nothing to charge him
        with which warrants the death penalty. I’ll teach him a lesson by flogging him and <char style="it">then
        </char>I’ll set him free.”<verse eid="LUK 23:22" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 23:23" />But they kept on piling on in loud voices demanding that he be crucified, and their shouts were overwhelming;<verse eid="LUK 23:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 23:24" />Pilate decided to acquiesce to their request. <verse eid="LUK 23:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 23:25" />He freed the one thrown in prison due to an insurrection, the one they kept asking <char style="it">for,
        </char>but he delivered Jesus over to their will and desire.<verse eid="LUK 23:25" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 23:26" />As they were leading him away, they pressed into service one Simon of Cyrene, who was coming <char style="it">home
        </char>from work, and put the cross on him to carry behind Jesus. <verse eid="LUK 23:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 23:27" />A large crowd of the folk people followed him, and women who continuously thumped <char style="it">their
        chests</char> and wept and wailed and sang dirges. <verse eid="LUK 23:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 23:28" />Jesus turned to them and said, <char style="wj">“Dear ladies</char><char style="sup">[e]</char><char
        style="wj">, don’t cry for me. Do, however, cry for yourselves and for your children, </char><verse eid="LUK 23:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 23:29" /><char style="wj">because—just like that—days will come in which they’ll say, ‘Blessed are the barren,
        the pregnant who never carried a child to term, the breasts that never breast-fed.’ </char><verse eid="LUK 23:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 23:30" /><char style="wj">Then they’ll commence going about…</char>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 23:30"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 23:30"><char style="wj">”…Saying to the mountains,</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 23:30"><char style="wj">‘Fall on us’</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 23:30"><char style="wj">And to the hills,</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="LUK 23:30"><char style="wj">‘Hide us’.</char><verse eid="LUK 23:30"/>
    </para>
    <para style="pi" />    <!-- Spacer line. No verse associated with it. -->
    <para style="m">
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 23:31" /><char style="wj">”If they’re doing these things with </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">pieces
        of</char></char><char style="wj"> freshly-cut lumber, then whatever happened to the dried-out </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">pieces</char></char><char style="wj">?</char><char style="sup">[C]</char><char
        style="wj">”</char><verse eid="LUK 23:31" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 23:32" />Now he and two other criminals along with him were being led <char style="it">in a spectacle of a procession</char>
        to be hoisted up <char style="it">on crosses and crucified</char>. <verse eid="LUK 23:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="LUK 23:33" />When they came to the place called The Skull, there he and the criminals were crucified, one to the right
        and the other to the left. <verse eid="LUK 23:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="LUK 23:34" />Jesus proceeded to say, <char style="wj">“Father, forgive them, since they don’t know what they’re doing.”</char><char
        style="sup">[f]</char> To divide his clothing up amongst themselves, they rolled dice<char style="sup">[g]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 23:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="LUK 23:35" />The folk-people stood <char style="it">around </char>watching. The rulers also began ridiculing him,
        saying, “He rescued others; if this guy is God’s Messiah, His Christ—the Chosen One, let him rescue himself.”<verse eid="LUK 23:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="LUK 23:36" />The soldiers also made fun of him by going up to him, bringing him spoiled-wine vinegar, <verse eid="LUK 23:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="LUK 23:37" />and saying, “If you’re the king of the Jews, rescue yourself.” <verse eid="LUK 23:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="LUK 23:38" />There was also a sign on top of him: “This guy is the king of the Jews.”<verse eid="LUK 23:38" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="LUK 23:39" />One of the criminals hung <char style="it">on a cross with him </char>kept on insulting him saying, “Aren’t
        you the Messiah, the Christ? Rescue yourself and us as well.” <verse eid="LUK 23:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="LUK 23:40" />But the other responded, scolding him, “Don’t you fear God even one bit because you’re facing the same
        sentence? <verse eid="LUK 23:40" />
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="LUK 23:41" />Sure, we’re being treated justly; indeed we deserve what’s been meted out to us. But this guy did nothing
        egregious.” <verse eid="LUK 23:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="LUK 23:42" />He said, “Jesus, remember me when you assume your preordained position in your kingdom<char style="sup">[h]</char>.”<verse eid="LUK 23:42" />
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="LUK 23:43" />And he said to him, “Mark my words, you’ll be with me in Paradise today.”<verse eid="LUK 23:43" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="LUK 23:44" />Around the time it reached noon<char style="sup">[i]</char>, darkness appeared over the entire land and
        persisted until three in the afternoon<char style="sup">[i]</char>, <verse eid="LUK 23:44" />
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="LUK 23:45" />while the sun was obscured. The temple curtain was torn in two down the middle. <verse eid="LUK 23:45" />
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="LUK 23:46" />Calling out in a loud voice, Jesus said, <char style="wj">“Father, into Your hands I entrust my spirit.”</char><verse eid="LUK 23:46" />
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="LUK 23:47" />Upon seeing what had happened, the centurion glorified God saying, “This man really was righteous.” <verse eid="LUK 23:47" />
      <verse number="48" style="v" sid="LUK 23:48" />And everyone in the crowd of bystanders, having witnessed what had happened, thumped their chests and
        began to leave. <verse eid="LUK 23:48" />
      <verse number="49" style="v" sid="LUK 23:49" />Everyone who knew him was standing at a distance to view these things, including the women from Galilee
        who too accompanied him as his followers.<verse eid="LUK 23:49" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="50" style="v" sid="LUK 23:50" />As events unfolded a man named Joseph, he being a councilman, and a good and righteous man <verse eid="LUK 23:50" />
      <verse number="51" style="v" sid="LUK 23:51" />(this fellow was not in agreement with the council and did not consent with what they did), from Arimathea,
        a city in Judea, one who was embracing God’s invitation for Him to be involved in his life (was receiving
        God’s kingdom)— <verse eid="LUK 23:51" />
      <verse number="52" style="v" sid="LUK 23:52" />This fellow approached Pilate and asked for Jesus’s body. <verse eid="LUK 23:52" />
      <verse number="53" style="v" sid="LUK 23:53" />He pulled him down, wrapped him in fine linen, and put him in a tomb hewn <char style="it">from rock</char>,
        in which nobody had yet been laid to rest.<verse eid="LUK 23:53" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="54" style="v" sid="LUK 23:54" />It was a preparation day, <char style="it">preparation for the Sabbath which would start the following
        day</char>, and the sun was about to set and <char style="it">consequently</char> begin <char style="it">the
        next day</char>, the Sabbath<char style="sup">[D]</char>. <verse eid="LUK 23:54" />
      <verse number="55" style="v" sid="LUK 23:55" />The women, those who had come down with him from Galilee, trailed behind following <char style="it">those
        who buried him</char>, saw the tomb and how his body was placed, <verse eid="LUK 23:55" />
      <verse number="56" style="v" sid="LUK 23:56" />and returned and prepared fragrance and ointment.
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 23:56">And while, yes, they were inactive on the Sabbath according to the commandment <char style="it">not to
        work on the Sabbath</char>…<char style="sup">[E]</char><verse eid="LUK 23:56"/>
    </para>
