  <!--   Chapter 24   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="24" style="c" sid="LUK 24" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="LUK 24:1" />…<char style="sup">[A]</char>Nevertheless, they got up early on Sunday, the first day of the week<char
        style="sup">[B]</char>, while it was still quite dark, and went to the tomb bringing the fragrance they
        had prepared. <verse eid="LUK 24:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="LUK 24:2" />They found that the stone had been rolled away from the tomb, <verse eid="LUK 24:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="LUK 24:3" />but after entering didn’t find the Lord Jesus’s body. <verse eid="LUK 24:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="LUK 24:4" />While <char style="it">the women</char> were in a state of perplexity over this, out of nowhere two men
        in gleaming clothing unexpectedly and abruptly showed up standing right next to them<char style="sup">[a]</char>,<verse eid="LUK 24:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="LUK 24:5" />and they became terrified of them. Turning their faces to the ground, they said to them, “Why are you
        looking for the Living One among the dead? <verse eid="LUK 24:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="LUK 24:6" />He’s not here; he’s been resurrected instead. Remember how he spoke to you while you were still in Galilee,<verse eid="LUK 24:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="LUK 24:7" />saying that the Man<char style="sup">[b]</char> must be betrayed and taken into custody by the hands
        of sinners, crucified, and resurrected on the third day.”<verse eid="LUK 24:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="LUK 24:8" />They remembered his remarks, <verse eid="LUK 24:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="LUK 24:9" />returned from the tomb, and announced all these things to the eleven and to everyone else. <verse eid="LUK 24:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="LUK 24:10" />Now Mary Magdalene, Joanna, and James’s mother Mary were <char style="it">there at the tomb</char>. The
        other women who were associated with them proceeded to tell these things to the missionaries<char style="sup">[c]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 24:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="LUK 24:11" />The impression that they took away from their presentation was that their remarks were just a lot of
        gibberish, and they refused to believe them. <verse eid="LUK 24:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="LUK 24:12" />But Peter got up and ran to the tomb, stooped and sees <char style="it">nothing but</char> the linens
        only, and left from there wondering to himself what had happened.<verse eid="LUK 24:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="LUK 24:13" />As events unfolded, on that very same day two of them were walking into a town, they being about seven
        miles/eleven kilometers<char style="sup">[C]</char> from Jerusalem, in <char style="it">a town </char>named
        Emmaus. <verse eid="LUK 24:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="LUK 24:14" />They were conversing with one another about how all of these things had transpired<char style="sup">[d]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 24:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="LUK 24:15" />It came to pass while they were conversing, making points and counterpoints, that Jesus himself approached
        them and walked together with them. <verse eid="LUK 24:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="LUK 24:16" />But their eyes were being held <char style="it">shut</char> from recognizing him<char style="sup">[e]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 24:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="LUK 24:17" />He said to them,
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 24:17"><char style="wj">“What’s up with these thoughts that you’ve bounced off each other while walking?”</char></para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 24:17">They stood still and looked depressed. <verse eid="LUK 24:17"/>
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="LUK 24:18" />The one named Cleopas replied, “Are you the only one in Jerusalem who’s totally clueless<char style="sup">[f]</char>and
        doesn’t know what’s happened these last few days?”<verse eid="LUK 24:18" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="LUK 24:19" />He said, <char style="wj">“Like what</char><char style="sup">[g]</char><char style="wj">?”</char>
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="LUK 24:19">They said, “Those things concerning Jesus of Nazareth, a man who became a mighty prophet in deed and
        in speech as considered by<char style="sup">[h]</char> God and by all the folk-people; <verse eid="LUK 24:19"/>
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="LUK 24:20" />furthermore, how our chief priests and rulers arrested him with the goal of sentencing him to death,
        and they crucified him. <verse eid="LUK 24:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="LUK 24:21" />We kept on hoping that he’s the one who’s going to do what it takes to liberate Israel; meanwhile, three
        days have gone by since these things happened and that hasn’t been the case. <verse eid="LUK 24:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="LUK 24:22" />But on top of that, some of the women who hang around us but had gone on an excursion caused us to lose
        our minds: they were terrified when they were at the tomb <verse eid="LUK 24:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="LUK 24:23" />and didn’t find his body there, and after returning they said that they even saw angels who appeared
        to them in visible form and <char style="it">the angels </char>say that he’s alive. <verse eid="LUK 24:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="LUK 24:24" />And certain members of our group left for the tomb and found things to be this way, just like the women
        told us, but didn’t see him.” <verse eid="LUK 24:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="LUK 24:25" />And he said to them, <char style="wj">“Oh, witless and slow in heart in believing in everything which
        the prophets have said. </char><verse eid="LUK 24:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="LUK 24:26" /><char style="wj">Didn’t the Messiah, the Christ, have to suffer these things and </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">then </char></char><char style="wj">enter into his glory?” </char><verse eid="LUK 24:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="LUK 24:27" />And having begun from the beginning of the Old Testament and walking through it<char style="sup">[i]</char>,
        he proceeded to interpret for them all those references in the Scriptures about him.<verse eid="LUK 24:27" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="LUK 24:28" />They got near to the town which they were going to, and he acted as if he was going to continue walking
        further. <verse eid="LUK 24:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="LUK 24:29" />They urged him, “Stay with us, since evening’s approaching and the day’s already come to a close.” He
        entered <char style="it">the house they arrived at as though he was going </char>to stay with them. <verse eid="LUK 24:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="LUK 24:30" />As a matter of course, while he was relaxed at the dinner table, he took the bread, gave thanks, broke
        it<char style="sup">[j]</char>, and gave it to them. <verse eid="LUK 24:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="LUK 24:31" />Their eyes were opened, and they recognized him, but he left and didn’t come back<char style="sup">[k]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 24:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="LUK 24:32" />They said to each other, “Weren’t our hearts burning within us as he was speaking to us on the way <char
        style="it">here</char>, as he kept on unfolding the <char style="it">meaning of </char>the Scriptures?”<verse eid="LUK 24:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="LUK 24:33" />And they got up that very moment and returned to Jerusalem and found the eleven gathered together, they
        and those associated with them, <verse eid="LUK 24:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="LUK 24:34" />saying that the Lord really had come back from the dead<char style="sup">[l]</char> and was seen by Simon.<verse eid="LUK 24:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="LUK 24:35" />They explained what happened on the road and how he came to be recognized by them in the breaking of
        bread<char style="sup">[j]</char>.<verse eid="LUK 24:35" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="LUK 24:36" />While they were still speaking these <char style="it">words, </char>he stood among them and <char style="it">then
        </char>says to them, “Peace <char style="it">be</char> with you<char style="sup">[m]</char>.” <verse eid="LUK 24:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="LUK 24:37" />They were startled and became frightened and thought they were looking at a ghost. <verse eid="LUK 24:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="LUK 24:38" />He said, <char style="wj">“Why have you become troubled, and what’s the reason these </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">erroneous </char></char><char style="wj">contemplations and conclusions you’ve drawn percolate
        up </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">from the base things of this earth and</char></char><char
        style="sup">[D]</char><char style="it"><char style="wj"> </char></char><char style="wj">into your collective
        heart? </char><verse eid="LUK 24:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="LUK 24:39" /><char style="wj">Take a look at my hands and feet, that I am he. Touch me and see that a ghost doesn’t
        have flesh and bone in the same way that you see me having.” </char><verse eid="LUK 24:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="LUK 24:40" />After he said this, he showed them <char style="it">his</char> hands and feet. <verse eid="LUK 24:40" />
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="LUK 24:41" />Out of the joy, wonder, and marvel <char style="it">of it all</char>, they<char style="it"> </char>just
        couldn’t believe it<char style="sup">[E]</char>, so he said to them, <char style="wj">“Do you have anything
        to eat here?” </char><verse eid="LUK 24:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="LUK 24:42" />They gave him a piece of broiled fish, <verse eid="LUK 24:42" />
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="LUK 24:43" />and he took it and ate it right in front of them.<verse eid="LUK 24:43" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="LUK 24:44" />He said to them, <char style="wj">“I spoke to you those very</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">
        </char></char><char style="wj">words of mine while I was still with you because all the verses in the
        Old Testament</char><char style="sup">[n]</char><char style="wj"> about me had to be fulfilled.” </char><verse eid="LUK 24:44" />
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="LUK 24:45" />Then he opened their minds for them to understand the Scriptures. <verse eid="LUK 24:45" />
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="LUK 24:46" />He said, <char style="wj">“…</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">Things turned out this way</char></char><char
        style="wj"> because the suffering of the Messiah, the Christ, and his resurrection from the dead on the
        third day had been captured in writing like that </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">in the Old
        Testament</char></char><char style="wj">, </char><verse eid="LUK 24:46" />
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="LUK 24:47" /><char style="wj">and </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">things turned out this way for you </char></char><char
        style="wj">to be authorized and commissioned by him to preach and proclaim to all nations a change in
        heart and in conduct leading to a forgiveness of sins</char><char style="sup">[o]</char><char style="wj">,
        initiated from Jerusalem: </char><verse eid="LUK 24:47" />
      <verse number="48" style="v" sid="LUK 24:48" /><char style="wj">You all will testify about</char><char style="sup">[p]</char><char style="wj"> these
        things. </char><verse eid="LUK 24:48" />
      <verse number="49" style="v" sid="LUK 24:49" /><char style="wj">And—get a load of this—I’m sending the promise of my Father </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">to come </char></char><char style="wj">upon you; but sit tight in the city until that time
        when you be clothed from on high in supernatural power.”</char><verse eid="LUK 24:49" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="50" style="v" sid="LUK 24:50" />He took them all the way out to Bethany and lifted up his hands and blessed them. <verse eid="LUK 24:50" />
      <verse number="51" style="v" sid="LUK 24:51" />It so happened while he was blessing them that he parted from them and was carried up into the sky, into
